---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Glossary — CS8833 Reference" currentPath="/glossary">

<div class="module-header">
  <div class="module-num">Reference</div>
  <h2>Glossary / Acronym Dictionary</h2>
</div>
<p style="color:var(--text-dim); font-family:'DM Mono',monospace; font-size:12px; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">Hover over <span class="acro-demo" style="color:var(--accent3); text-decoration:underline dotted rgba(79,247,176,0.5); cursor:help;">underlined acronyms</span> anywhere in the document for inline tooltips. Full definitions below.</p>

<div class="glossary-grid">
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">2LD</div><div class="g-def">Second-Level Domain — e.g., gatech in gatech.edu (with .edu being the top-level domain)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ACH</div><div class="g-def">Automated Clearing House (financial payments context) — OR — Analysis of Competing Hypotheses (intelligence analysis method that fights confirmation bias)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">APT</div><div class="g-def">Advanced Persistent Threat — originally US military terminology for targeted, persistent attackers (vs. opportunistic). Commercially overused to mean "nation-state actor," though semantically tied to behavior, not identity.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">AppSec</div><div class="g-def">Application Security — the set of tactics, techniques, and procedures that the security team uses to secure the output and behaviors of the software engineering organization. Scope includes proprietary code and integrated open source; excludes COTS software.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ASM</div><div class="g-def">Attack Surface Management — continuous discovery and monitoring of all externally visible assets, going beyond traditional vulnerability scanning by starting from business names and domains rather than known IP lists. ASM tools automatically discover subdomains, related domains (via WHOIS), cloud assets, and map them against known vulnerabilities.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ATO</div><div class="g-def">Account Takeover — unauthorized access to a user account, typically via credential theft or stuffing</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">BYOD</div><div class="g-def">Bring Your Own Device — policy allowing employees to use personal devices (phones, laptops) for work purposes, typically with security requirements like enrollment, remote wipe capability, or containerized applications.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">BEC</div><div class="g-def">Business Email Compromise — attacker has actual control of a legitimate corporate email account (more dangerous than spoofing)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">BES</div><div class="g-def">Business Email Spoofing — spoofing the display name in the "From" field without controlling the actual domain. Detectable via header analysis.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">BISO</div><div class="g-def">Business Information Security Officer — security leadership role aligned to a specific business unit or subsidiary</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">C2</div><div class="g-def">Command and Control — the infrastructure and processes used by attackers to remotely control compromised systems ("phone home" traffic)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CI/CD</div><div class="g-def">Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment — modern software development practice where code changes are automatically built, tested, and deployed to production in small increments. Segregation of duties between code authors and deployers remains an important audit control.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CIA</div><div class="g-def">Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability — the classic information security triad defining the properties that controls are designed to protect</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CINC</div><div class="g-def">Cybersecurity Incident — a unique-identified record of a confirmed or suspected cyber security event requiring formal response</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CIRP</div><div class="g-def">Cyber Incident Response Procedure — the governing document that defines how incidents are classified, escalated, and resolved</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CISO</div><div class="g-def">Chief Information Security Officer — the executive responsible for an organization's information security program</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">COTS</div><div class="g-def">Commercial Off-The-Shelf — pre-built software purchased from vendors (e.g., Oracle, SolarWinds). Outside AppSec's direct code review scope; secured instead through contracts, vendor questionnaires, and zero-trust architecture (segmentation, egress controls, monitoring).</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">COBIT</div><div class="g-def">Control Objectives for Information Technologies — a governance framework for IT management, published by ISACA</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CRO</div><div class="g-def">Chief Risk Officer — executive responsible for enterprise risk management; one of the possible CISO reporting lines</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CSRF</div><div class="g-def">Cross-Site Request Forgery — web attack that co-opts a user's authenticated session to perform actions they didn't intend, particularly dangerous in cloud environments where actions can grant access to third parties.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CTI</div><div class="g-def">Cyber Threat Intelligence — the collection, analysis, and dissemination of information about cyber threats</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CVE</div><div class="g-def">Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures — a standard identifier format for publicly disclosed cybersecurity vulnerabilities</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">CVSS</div><div class="g-def">Common Vulnerability Scoring System — a standardized framework for rating the severity of security vulnerabilities, providing a numerical score (0-10) used as a starting point for risk assessment before organizational context is applied.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">DAC</div><div class="g-def">Discretionary Access Control — access control where the owner of a resource controls who can access it</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">DAST</div><div class="g-def">Dynamic Application Security Testing — security testing performed against a running web application from the outside (browser perspective). Tools like Burp Suite intercept and modify HTTP requests to probe for vulnerabilities. Higher fidelity than SAST because findings are proven exploitable.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">DDW</div><div class="g-def">Deep and Dark Web — resources unavailable via standard search engines due to authentication or network-level restrictions; often associated with criminal forums</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">DFIR</div><div class="g-def">Digital Forensics and Incident Response — IR augmented with forensic evidence collection, preservation, and legal chain of custody</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">DLP</div><div class="g-def">Data Loss/Leakage Prevention — technology that detects and prevents unauthorized transmission of sensitive data</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">DPO</div><div class="g-def">Data Privacy Officer — responsible for ensuring compliance with data privacy laws (GDPR, CCPA, etc.); must be engaged on any potential data disclosure regardless of incident severity</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">EDR</div><div class="g-def">Endpoint Detection and Response — endpoint security tool that records and monitors system behavior to detect and investigate threats</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">EPP</div><div class="g-def">Endpoint Protection Platform — traditional antivirus evolved to include behavioral detection; the prevention layer (vs. EDR's detection/response layer)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">FAIR</div><div class="g-def">Factor Analysis of Information Risk — the leading quantitative risk model that expresses risk in financial terms (annualized loss expectancy) by decomposing risk into measurable factors: Loss Event Frequency × Loss Magnitude. Used for high-stakes investment decisions where qualitative scoring isn't precise enough.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">FQDN</div><div class="g-def">Fully Qualified Domain Name — the complete, unambiguous domain name (e.g., prism.gatech.edu), as opposed to an unqualified hostname (e.g., just "prism")</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">GC</div><div class="g-def">General Counsel — the organization's chief legal officer; key stakeholder in incident response, data breach notifications, and regulatory matters</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">GRC</div><div class="g-def">Governance, Risk, and Compliance — the second-line function responsible for policy, risk management, and regulatory compliance</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">HSM</div><div class="g-def">Hardware Security Module — a physical device that safeguards and manages cryptographic keys; used for high-assurance encryption operations</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IAM</div><div class="g-def">Identity and Access Management — the framework for managing digital identities and controlling access to resources</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IDOR</div><div class="g-def">Insecure Direct Object Reference — web vulnerability where changing a parameter value (e.g., incrementing a company ID in a URL) exposes another user's data without authorization checks. Prevention requires complete mediation: verify authorization on every data access, not just at login.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IDS</div><div class="g-def">Intrusion Detection System — passive monitoring tool that detects suspicious activity and generates alerts (does not block)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IFF</div><div class="g-def">Identification Friend or Foe — a deconfliction protocol borrowed from military aviation, used during red team engagements to allow defenders to confirm whether detected activity is the red team or a real adversary before escalating to law enforcement or triggering breach notifications.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IIA</div><div class="g-def">Institute of Internal Auditors — professional body that defines the Three Lines Model for organizational governance and risk management</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IOC</div><div class="g-def">Indicator of Compromise — specific technical artifacts (file hashes, IP addresses, domains) associated with known attacks; tactical intelligence with short shelf life</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IPS</div><div class="g-def">Intrusion Prevention System — active (inline) counterpart to IDS; can block detected threats in real time but carries production risk if misconfigured</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ITW</div><div class="g-def">In The Wild — threat intelligence term meaning a vulnerability is currently being actively exploited by adversaries in real-world attacks, as opposed to being only theoretical or proof-of-concept.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">IR</div><div class="g-def">Incident Response (security context) — OR — Investor Relations (corporate context). Always clarify when speaking cross-functionally.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ISAC</div><div class="g-def">Information Sharing and Analysis Center — sector-based communities for sharing threat intelligence among industry peers (FS-ISAC, H-ISAC, E-ISAC, etc.)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ISMS</div><div class="g-def">Information Security Management System — the overarching framework of policies, procedures, and controls for managing information security (ISO 27001 defines requirements for an ISMS)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">ITIL</div><div class="g-def">Information Technology Infrastructure Library — a set of IT service management practices; relevant for aligning security operations with broader IT operations</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">Kill Chain</div><div class="g-def">The "Cyber Kill Chain" (Lockheed Martin, 2011) — maps attacks across: Reconnaissance → Weaponization → Delivery → Exploitation → Installation → C2 → Actions on Objectives</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MAC</div><div class="g-def">Mandatory Access Control — access control enforced by the system based on classifications (e.g., government security labels), not owner discretion</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MECE</div><div class="g-def">Mutually Exclusive, Collectively Exhaustive — a taxonomy design principle ensuring categories don't overlap and collectively cover all cases</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MITRE ATT&amp;CK</div><div class="g-def">A MITRE framework defining a MECE taxonomy of adversary techniques organized by kill chain phases; 500+ techniques mapped across 14 tactic categories</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MNPI</div><div class="g-def">Material Non-Public Information — information that has not been disclosed publicly and could affect an investor's decision (insider trading context); theft of MNPI is a Data Disclosure threat objective</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MSSP</div><div class="g-def">Managed Security Service Provider — a third party that operates security functions (commonly SOC/monitoring) on behalf of an organization</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MTTC</div><div class="g-def">Mean Time to Contain — average time from incident detection to confirmed containment of the threat</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MTTD</div><div class="g-def">Mean Time to Detect — average time between when a threat event begins and when it is detected</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">MTTR</div><div class="g-def">Mean Time to Respond — average time from detection to the beginning of active response actions</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">NAC</div><div class="g-def">Network Access Control — technology that enforces security policies before granting device access to a network</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">NetFlow</div><div class="g-def">A network protocol and data format for collecting IP traffic metadata (source/dest IP, port, bytes) — useful for forensics without storing full packet captures</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">NIST</div><div class="g-def">National Institute of Standards and Technology — US federal agency that publishes widely adopted cybersecurity frameworks (CSF, SP 800-series)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">OINC</div><div class="g-def">Operational Incident — the operations counterpart to a CINC; must maintain parallel severity numbering and defined trigger rules between OINC and CINC systems</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">OIRP</div><div class="g-def">Operational Incident Response Procedure — the operations counterpart to the CIRP</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">OPSEC</div><div class="g-def">Operational Security — practices used to protect one's own identity and activities from adversary observation. FLOPSec = failed OPSEC that attracts more attention than it conceals.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">OSINT</div><div class="g-def">Open Source Intelligence — intelligence gathered from publicly available sources (LinkedIn, social media, search engines, job postings)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">PAM</div><div class="g-def">Privileged Access Management — controls governing access to administrative/privileged accounts; among the most critical controls for limiting blast radius</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">pDNS</div><div class="g-def">Passive DNS — data collected from DNS resolvers that records queries and responses without making them directly; useful for researching domain history covertly</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">PHNV</div><div class="g-def">Potentially Harmful New Vulnerability — a newly reported vulnerability in widely-used software that requires investigation to determine organizational impact. Enters the risk register as a potential risk rather than being treated as an incident.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">PHI</div><div class="g-def">Protected Health Information — health data protected under HIPAA; a Data Disclosure threat objective sub-category</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">PII</div><div class="g-def">Personally Identifiable Information — any data that can identify a specific individual; triggers privacy law obligations upon disclosure</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">POC</div><div class="g-def">Proof of Concept — a demonstration that a vulnerability can be exploited, either as published exploit code or a custom script. The existence of a POC increases the likelihood component of a risk score because adversaries can replicate it.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">RAMP</div><div class="g-def">Risk Assessment Management Procedure — the governing document that defines how the risk register is used, how risks are triaged and scored, how SLAs are applied, and how remediation workflows operate. The risk management parallel to the CIRP.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">RASP</div><div class="g-def">Runtime Application Self-Protection — security tools that run inside application processes, monitoring memory and stopping suspicious activity in real-time. Operationally risky: high false positive rates in early deployment can kill legitimate processes.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">RBAC</div><div class="g-def">Role-Based Access Control — access control where permissions are assigned to roles, and users are assigned to roles (vs. individual permissions per user)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">RFI</div><div class="g-def">Request for Information — a targeted intelligence request to a sharing community (e.g., "please share anything on adversaries targeting oil distribution networks")</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">RISO</div><div class="g-def">Regional Information Security Officer — geographically aligned security leadership role (Americas/EMEA/APAC)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">RPZ</div><div class="g-def">Response Policy Zone — a DNS feature allowing resolvers to block or redirect queries to known-malicious domains at the resolver level</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SAST</div><div class="g-def">Static Application Security Testing — security review of source code before compilation or deployment, often via IDE plugins that flag issues in real-time during development. Catches issues early but has high false positive rates due to lack of runtime context.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SCA</div><div class="g-def">Software Composition Analysis — analysis of third-party libraries and open-source components integrated into applications, checking versions against known vulnerability databases. Sophistication ranges from basic (is the library present?) to advanced (are the specific vulnerable methods actually called?).</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SDLC</div><div class="g-def">Software Development Lifecycle — the document governing software engineering practices: approved languages, repository structure, check-in/checkout procedures, pull request approvals, environment management (dev/test/prod). Predates security; the SESP adds security requirements on top of it.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SESP</div><div class="g-def">Software Engineering Security Policy — the security-specific policy document for software engineers defining requirements for logging, input validation, secrets management, IAM integration, architectural standards, and web security. Non-compliance findings feed into the risk register.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SIEM</div><div class="g-def">Security Information and Event Management — a log aggregation platform with correlation logic that converts raw events into actionable alerts</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SOAR</div><div class="g-def">Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response — platforms that automate security workflows and runbooks, reducing analyst time on repetitive tasks</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SOC</div><div class="g-def">Security Operations Center — tiered team (L1/L2/L3) responsible for monitoring, detection, triage, and initial response</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SQLi</div><div class="g-def">SQL Injection — an attack that inserts malicious SQL code into a query to manipulate a database; a common Data Disclosure attack vector</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">SSRF</div><div class="g-def">Server-Side Request Forgery — attack that co-opts a server's network access and permissions to reach internal resources the attacker shouldn't be able to access. Particularly dangerous in cloud environments where servers can access internal metadata services and adjacent infrastructure.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">STIX/TAXII</div><div class="g-def">Structured Threat Information Expression / Trusted Automated eXchange of Intelligence Information — OASIS standards for formatting and sharing threat intelligence data between organizations</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">TIP</div><div class="g-def">Threat Intelligence Platform — software that ingests, normalizes, and operationalizes IOCs and threat intelligence from multiple sources</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">TLD</div><div class="g-def">Top-Level Domain — .com, .net, .edu, etc. Includes country-code TLDs (ccTLDs: .ru, .us) and generic TLDs (gTLDs: .google, .club)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">TLP</div><div class="g-def">Traffic Light Protocol — a FIRST.org standard for classifying threat intelligence sharing permissions: RED (recipient only) → AMBER → GREEN → CLEAR (public)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">TPRM</div><div class="g-def">Third-Party Risk Management — the discipline of assessing and monitoring security risks introduced by vendors, suppliers, and partners. Operates through a chain of agreements (contracts), tests (questionnaires, SOC 2, audits), and enforcement (commercial choice, contract penalties).</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">TTP</div><div class="g-def">Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures — the habits, patterns, and tradecraft correlated with specific adversary groups or campaigns. MITRE ATT&amp;CK maps TTPs to kill chain phases.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">UDRP</div><div class="g-def">Uniform Domain-Name Dispute-Resolution Policy — ICANN's formal mechanism for resolving domain name disputes and cybersquatting (cost: ~$1,500; timeline: weeks to months)</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">UCE</div><div class="g-def">Unsolicited Commercial Email — spam; technically not a phishing attack, though often reported as one by well-meaning employees</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">VSAQ</div><div class="g-def">Vendor Security Assessment Questionnaire — a standardized security questionnaire format used by organizations to evaluate the security posture of their vendors and partners.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">VDP</div><div class="g-def">Vulnerability Disclosure Program — a formal channel for external researchers to responsibly report security vulnerabilities to an organization</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">VEC</div><div class="g-def">Vendor Email Compromise — BEC targeting a trusted vendor's email account to redirect payments or extract information from their customers</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">WAF</div><div class="g-def">Web Application Firewall — an inline (active) application-layer security control that inspects and filters HTTP/HTTPS traffic</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">WEF</div><div class="g-def">Windows Event Forwarding — a Windows feature that forwards event log data from endpoints to a central collector; high-volume but valuable for forensics</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">WHOIS</div><div class="g-def">A protocol and data format for identifying registrant contact information for domain names and internet networks</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">XSS</div><div class="g-def">Cross-Site Scripting — web vulnerability where an attacker injects JavaScript that executes in another user's browser context. Stored XSS (persisted in a forum post or comment) is more dangerous than reflected XSS. Typically part of a kill chain rather than a standalone threat objective.</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">XDR</div><div class="g-def">Extended Detection and Response — evolution of EDR that correlates telemetry across endpoints, network, cloud, and identity for unified threat detection</div></div>
  <div class="g-item"><div class="g-term">YARA</div><div class="g-def">Yet Another Recursive Acronym — a pattern-matching language for describing and identifying malware families based on file content characteristics (broader than hash-based matching)</div></div>
</div>

</BaseLayout>
